args: Filing reports is as much a part of the job\nas fieldwork. Stop pouting and do it.\nPerfectly.
Hee hee. You're right. I'm on it!
You always try to be perfect because you\nwant to make your father proud, right?
Nevin told me you always push yourself\nto rise to Uriel's expectations of you.
Thinking about that made me feel\nall warm and fuzzy. The laugh just\nkind of slipped out.
Um... Was it something I said?
Sixty points. You fail.\nFlunk out entirely, in fact.
WHAT?! Why would I—oh!\nAre you bashful about it?
Does my current tone strike you as\nbashful, Pinon?
No. You mostly seem super mad.
Correct. Ugh... Nevin chose quite the\nflippant rumor to spread this time.
But I suppose this is an opportunity to\neducate a colleague, as her senior.
As you're clearly so curious, I'll elucidate\nwhy we must be perfect at all times.\nAnd about the station we both occupy.
Indeed. We are Sigil-bound to the angels.\nWhat happens if that bond is severed?
The apostle dies, and the angel suffers ill\neffects as well. They have to find a new\napostle to bond with as soon as possible.
Correct. This is why a program to scout and\ntrain new candidates exists at Church HQ.
Though few within the Church know of its\nexistence, they gather promising children\nthere and raise them to be apostles.
Should something befall us, they would\ndispatch a replacement immediately.
Then on to the next point. Angels can\nsever the Sigil bond unilaterally at will.
I knew that, too. Though I imagine things\nwould have to be REALLY serious for them\nto go that route.
They'd be putting themselves in danger,\nafter all.
Thirteen points. It seems you've been\ncoddled rather severely until now.
Hey, now! I don't care if you talk down to\nme, but don't go badmouthing Gabriel!
Your feelings notwithstanding, it remains\ntrue that you are naive. Gabriel's methods\nare clearly lacking.
It is manifestly clear that you have no\ngrasp of your own position.
I'm an apostle! I understand that just fine!
My point is that you have failed to grasp\nwhat that MEANS. You do not understand\nwhat an apostle is, fundamentally.
It's a servant of the Goddess Ilia who—
That's merely the official line. I'm asking\nif you know the true essence of the role.
They spin a pretty narrative about deities\nand holy missions, but that is the bottom\nline.
When we die, they just bring in the next\none. Neither you nor I have any real value\nor significance beyond that.
And that being the case, what meaning is\nthere to you and I being here right now?
What identifies us as individuals?\nWhat justifies our existence in this world?
That's not... Why should we have to\njustify our existence in the first place?
Gabriel has shown me nothing but love.\nI'm not just some tool to her, to use up\nand throw away.
If that is your best argument for the value\nof your own existence, I must conclude\nthat you are hopelessly naive.
You fail to meet the barest minimum of\ncriteria as an apostle.
I'll tell you what the answer is:\nto embody perfection as an apostle.\nTo make yourself irreplaceable.
So in your eyes, it's be flawless or get\ntossed to the wayside. Is that why you're\nso strict about everything?
If I'm imperfect, I'm meaningless.\nThat is why I reach ever higher.
Ours is not a role where we can indulge\nin pretty, escapist fantasies of love and\npiety and whatever else.
Now do you understand the position\nyou're in?
Oh, I definitely understand YOUR\nview on the matter now, Faris.
I take that to mean you choose to disagree.\nHmph. Sixteen points...
Hey, uh, did I come at a bad time?\nTension's a liiittle thick in here.
It's fine. Do you require something?
Okay, yeah, I would've needed my GOOD\nknife to cut that tension. Ah well.\nGuess this is a good opportunity.
Your orders are as follows.\nHeed my words closely.
Children have been disappearing from\na certain orphanage.
Sealing stones may be involved where\nsudden changes in human behavior are\nobserved.
We cannot overlook this incident.\nUncover the truth behind these events\nand deal with the cause accordingly.
This is the place. Looks like your\neveryday orphanage from here.
This orphanage is...a place\nI'm well acquainted with.
